DISTRIBUTION

How a compose-bridge version reaches consumers — from a local version
bump to an artifact the E2E test workflows pull at run time.

compose-bridge is an internal test tool, not a published vendor
package. Distribution lives entirely inside GitHub Actions artifacts;
there is no R2 mirror and no public download URL.


Pipeline overview
-----------------

  1. Bump        Local script updates both version sources and creates
                 a single commit on dev/tests/compose-bridge.
  2. Verify      Operator runs test_runner.py locally to confirm the
                 FFI surface still works end-to-end.
  3. Push        Push the bump commit. No CI fires on push — the
                 publish workflow is the only CI entry point.
  4. Publish     Operator runs publish.sh, which dispatches the
                 publish workflow with no arguments.
  5. Build       Publish workflow extracts version from source,
                 validates the Go-side match, then builds linux-amd64,
                 linux-arm64, and darwin-arm64 (signed + notarized).
  6. Package     Per-platform zips attached as GitHub Actions
                 artifacts with 90-day retention.
  7. Consumption Consuming branches (dev/daemon, dev/firewall-bridge)
                 pull via gh CLI targeting the latest successful run.


Stage 1 — Bump
--------------

  .github/scripts/bump.sh [major|minor|patch]

  Defaults to patch. Updates BOTH version sources atomically:

      compose_bridge/__init__.py  →  __version__
      src/version.go              →  BridgeVersionStr

  Refuses to run if the two are already out of sync. Verifies the
  post-write values, then creates a single commit:

      Bump v<NEW_VERSION>


Stage 2 — Verify
----------------

  python test_runner.py --build

  Rebuilds the shared library for the host platform, then runs the
  dogfood suite: up → ps → exec (echo, env, nonzero exit) → logs →
  down against a trivial alpine compose file. All checks must pass
  before trusting the bump.


Stage 3 — Push
--------------

  git push origin dev/tests/compose-bridge

  No CI test or build workflow runs on push. compose-bridge doesn't
  maintain one — its FFI surface is exercised transitively by the
  consuming branches' E2E jobs every time they fetch-and-run it, so
  regressions surface there rather than here.


Stage 4 — Publish trigger
-------------------------

  .github/scripts/publish.sh

  No arguments. Reads the version from compose_bridge/__init__.py and
  dispatches publish-compose-bridge.yml on the dev/tests/compose-bridge
  ref via the GitHub CLI (gh workflow run).


Stage 5 — Publish workflow
--------------------------

  publish-compose-bridge.yml runs four jobs:

      extract-version  Reads compose_bridge/__init__.py. Validates
                       that src/version.go matches. Aborts the run
                       on mismatch.

      build-linux      Matrix over amd64 and arm64. Go build with
                       CGO_ENABLED=1, cross-compile via
                       aarch64-linux-gnu-gcc for arm64.

      build-macos      macos-26 runner. Builds darwin-arm64 then
                       signs with the "Developer ID Application"
                       certificate, submits to notarytool, waits for
                       approval.

      package          Assembles per-platform zips, attaches as
                       GitHub Actions artifacts, deletes the
                       intermediate per-arch build artifacts.


Stage 6 — Artifact storage
--------------------------

  Location : GitHub Actions run artifacts (no R2, no public URL)
  Retention: 90 days

  Each successful publish uploads three artifacts:

      compose-bridge-<VERSION>-linux-amd64
      compose-bridge-<VERSION>-linux-arm64
      compose-bridge-<VERSION>-darwin-arm64

  Each zip contains a single top-level compose_bridge/ directory:

      compose_bridge/
        __init__.py
        _ffi.py
        bridge.py
        types.py
        VERSION
        compose_bridge-<PLATFORM>.<ext>   (.dylib for darwin, .so for linux)

  VERSION is populated from the extracted source version at package
  time; nothing on disk in the source tree.


Stage 7 — Consumption
---------------------

  Consumers do not fetch compose-bridge from a URL. They use the
  GitHub CLI against the publish workflow:

      # Latest successful run of publish-compose-bridge.yml
      RUN=$(gh run list --workflow publish-compose-bridge.yml \
          --status success --limit 1 --json databaseId \
          --jq '.[0].databaseId')

      # Per-platform artifact from that run
      ARTIFACT=$(gh api /repos/.../actions/runs/$RUN/artifacts \
          --jq '.artifacts[] | select(.name | endswith("-linux-amd64")) | .name' \
          | head -1)

      gh run download "$RUN" --name "$ARTIFACT"

  This pattern is implemented in two places:

      dev/daemon           tools/lib/test.sh::cmd_fetch_compose_bridge
      dev/firewall-bridge  fetch_compose_bridge.sh

  Both track the latest successful run — no pinned run id, no pinned
  version. Updating is just a matter of re-running the fetch; the
  current version lives inside the downloaded zip's VERSION file.


End-to-end example
------------------

  $ .github/scripts/bump.sh patch
  1.0.0 → 1.0.1
  [dev/tests/compose-bridge abcdef0] Bump v1.0.1

  $ python test_runner.py --build
  ...
  RESULTS: 13/13 passed, 0 failed

  $ git push origin dev/tests/compose-bridge

  $ .github/scripts/publish.sh
  Version : v1.0.1
  Workflow: publish-compose-bridge.yml
  Ref     : dev/tests/compose-bridge
  Triggered. Watch: gh run list --repo ARAS-Workspace/phantom-wg --workflow publish-compose-bridge.yml

  # → publish workflow runs extract-version → build-linux → build-macos → package
  #   ~20-35 min total (macOS notarization dominates).

  # On dev/daemon:
  $ ./tools/dev.sh fetch-compose-bridge
  Locating latest successful publish-compose-bridge.yml...
  Resolving artifact for linux-amd64 in run ...
  Fetching compose-bridge-1.0.1-linux-amd64 (run ...)...
  Installed to lib/compose_bridge/


Rollback
--------

  GitHub retains 90 days of artifacts, so rollback is implicit:

  1. Bump again (patch) and publish a corrected version.
  2. Consumers' fetch scripts re-run naturally pick up the new
     "latest successful" run.
  3. The previous artifact remains retrievable by explicit run id
     until it falls off the 90-day retention window.


Notes
-----

  * compose-bridge is not in the vendor pack distributed via R2. Its
    audience is internal CI only.

  * The macOS artifact is signed and notarized even though no end
    user downloads it — keeps dev-on-macOS equivalent to CI.

  * Published artifacts use the suffix <-linux-amd64 | -linux-arm64
    | -darwin-arm64>; consumers match by suffix so the version prefix
    can change freely without touching the fetch scripts.
